# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: berry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The **ABC model of flower development** is a scientific model of the process by which flowering plants produce a pattern of gene expression in meristems that leads to the appearance of an organ oriented towards sexual reproduction, a flower.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The latter phase has been modelled using the **ABC model**, which aims to describe the biological basis of the process from the perspective of molecular and developmental genetics.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] An external stimulus is required in order to trigger the differentiation of the meristem into a flower meristem.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] This stimulus will activate mitotic cell division in the apical meristem, particularly on its sides where new primordia are formed.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] This same stimulus will also cause the meristem to follow a developmental pattern that will lead to the growth of floral meristems as opposed to vegetative meristems.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The main difference between these two types of meristem, apart from the obvious disparity between the objective organ, is the verticillate (or whorled) phyllotaxis, that is, the absence of stem elongation among the successive whorls or verticils of the primordium.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] These verticils follow an acropetal development, giving rise to sepals, petals, stamens and carpels.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Another difference from vegetative axillary meristems is that the floral meristem is "determined", which means that, once differentiated, its cells will no longer divide.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The identity of the organs present in the four floral verticils is a consequence of the interaction of at least three types of gene products, each with distinct functions.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] According to the ABC model, functions A and C are required in order to determine the identity of the verticils of the perianth and the reproductive verticils, respectively.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] These functions are exclusive and the absence of one of them means that the other will determine the identity of all the floral verticils.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B function allows the differentiation of petals from sepals in the secondary verticil, as well as the differentiation of the stamen from the carpel on the tertiary verticil.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Goethe's **foliar theory** was formulated in the 18th century and it suggests that the constituent parts of a flower are structurally modified leaves, which are functionally specialized for reproduction or protection.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The transition from the vegetative phase to a reproductive phase involves a dramatic change in the plant's vital cycle, perhaps the most important one, as the process must be carried out correctly in order to guarantee that the plant produces descendants.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] This transition is characterised by the induction and development of the meristem of the inflorescence, which will produce a collection of flowers or one flower.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] This morphogenetic change contains both endogenous and exogenous elements: For example, in order for the change to be initiated the plant must have a certain number of leaves and contain a certain level of total biomass.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Certain environmental conditions are also required such as a characteristic photoperiod.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Plant hormones play an important part in the process, with the gibberellins having a particularly important role.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are many signals that regulate the molecular biology of the process.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The following three genes in *Arabidopsis thaliana* possess both common and independent functions in floral transition: *FLOWERING LOCUS T* (*FT*), *LEAFY* (*LFY*), *SUPPRESSOR OF OVEREXPRESSION OF CONSTANS1* (*SOC1*, also called *AGAMOUS-LIKE20*).
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] *SOC1* is a MADS-box-type gene, which integrates responses to photoperiod, vernalization and gibberellins.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The meristem can be defined as the tissue or group of plant tissues that contain undifferentiated stem cells, which are capable of producing any type of cell tissue.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Their maintenance and development, both in the vegetative meristem or the meristem of the inflorescence is controlled by genetic cell fate determination mechanisms.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that a number of genes will directly regulate, for example, the maintenance of the stem cell's characteristics (gene *WUSCHEL* or *WUS*), and others will act via negative feedback mechanisms in order to inhibit a characteristic (gene *CLAVATA* or *CLV*).
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this way both mechanisms give rise to a feedback loop, which along with other elements lend a great deal of robustness to the system.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Along with the *WUS* gene the *SHOOTMERISTEMLESS* (*STM*) gene also represses the differentiation of the meristematic dome.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] This gene acts by inhibiting the possible differentiation of the stem cells but still allows cell division in the daughter cells, which, had they been allowed to differentiate, would have given rise to distinct organs.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] A flower's anatomy, as defined by the presence of a series of organs (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels) positioned according to a given pattern, facilitate sexual reproduction in flowering plants.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model of flower development was first formulated by George Haughn and Chris Somerville in 1988.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was first used as a model to describe the collection of genetic mechanisms that establish floral organ identity in the Rosids, as exemplified by *Arabidopsis thaliana*, and the Asterids, as demonstrated by *Antirrhinum majus*.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both species have four verticils (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels), which are defined by the differential expression of a number of homeotic genes present in each verticil.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that the sepals are solely characterized by the expression of A genes, while the petals are characterized by the co-expression of A and B genes.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B and C genes establish the identity of the stamens and the carpels only require C genes to be active.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Type A and C genes are reciprocally antagonistic.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The fact that these homeotic genes determine an organ's identity becomes evident when a gene that represents a particular function, for example the A gene, is not expressed.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* this loss results in a flower which is composed of one verticil of carpels, another containing stamens and another of carpels.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] This method for studying gene function uses reverse genetics techniques to produce transgenic plants that contain a mechanism for gene silencing through RNA interference.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In other studies, using forward genetics techniques such as genetic mapping, it is the analysis of the phenotypes of flowers with structural anomalies that leads to the cloning of the gene of interest.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The flowers may possess a non-functional or over expressed allele for the gene being studied.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The existence of two supplementary functions, D and E, have also been proposed in addition to the A, B and C functions already discussed.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function D specifies the identity of the ovule, as a separate reproductive function from the development of the carpels, which occurs after their determination.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function E relates to a physiological requirement that is a characteristic of all floral verticils, although, it was initially described as necessary for the development of the three innermost verticils (Function E *sensu stricto*).
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, its broader definition (*sensu lato*) suggests that it is required in the four verticils.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The gene products of genes with D and E functions are also MADS-box genes.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The methodology for studying flower development involves two steps.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Firstly, the identification of the exact genes required for determining the identity of the floral meristem.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* these include APETALA1 (*AP1*) and LEAFY (*LFY*).
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Secondly, genetic analysis is carried out on the aberrant phenotypes for the relative characteristics of the flowers, which allows the characterization of the homeotic genes implicated in the process.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are a great many mutations that affect floral morphology, although the analysis of these mutants is a recent development.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Supporting evidence for the existence of these mutations comes from the fact that a large number affect the identity of floral organs.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] For example, some organs develop in a location where others should develop.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is called homeotic mutation, which is analogous to HOX gene mutations found in *Drosophila*.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* and *Antirrhinum*, the two taxa on which models are based, these mutations always affect adjacent verticils.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Cloning studies have been carried out on DNA in the genes associated with the affected homeotic functions in the mutants discussed above.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] These studies used serial analysis of gene expression throughout floral development to show patterns of tissue expression, which, in general, correspond with the predictions of the ABC model.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The nature of these genes corresponds to that of transcription factors, which, as expected, have analogous structures to a group of factors contained in yeasts and animal cells.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] This group is called MADS, which is an acronym for the different factors contained in the group.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] These MADS factors have been detected in all the vegetable species studied, although the involvement of other elements involved in the regulation of gene expression cannot be discounted.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, function A is mainly represented by two genes *APETALA1* (*AP1)* and *APETALA2* (*AP2*) *AP1* is a MADS-box type gene, while *AP2* belongs to the family of genes that contains AP2, which it gives its name to and which consists of transcription factors that are only found in plants.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] AP2 has also been shown to complex with the co-repressor TOPLESS (TPL) in developing floral buds to repress the C-class gene *AGAMOUS* (*AG*).
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] *AP2* not only functions in the first two verticils, but also in the remaining two, in developing ovules and even in leaves.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] It is also likely that post-transcriptional regulation exists, which controls its A function, or even that it has other purposes in the determination of organ identity independent of that mentioned here.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Antirrhinum*, the orthologous gene to *AP1* is *SQUAMOSA* (*SQUA*), which also has a particular impact on the floral meristem.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs for *AP2* are *LIPLESS1* (*LIP1*) and *LIPLESS2* (*LIP2*), which have a redundant function and are of special interest in the development of sepals, petals and ovules.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] A total of three genes have been isolated from *Petunia hybrida* that are similar to *AP2*: *P. hybrida APETALA2A* (*PhAP2A*), *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] *PhAP2A* is, to a large degree, homologous with the *AP2* gene of *Arabidopsis*, both in its sequence and in its expression pattern, which suggests that the two genes are orthologs.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The proteins *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*, on the other hand, are slightly different, even though they belong to the family of transcription factors that are similar to *AP2*.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition they are expressed in different ways, although they are very similar in comparison with *PhAP2A*.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In fact, the mutants for these genes do not show the usual phenotype, that of the null alleles of A genes.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* the type-B function mainly arises from two genes, *APETALA3* (*AP3*) and *PISTILLATA* (*PI*), both of which are MADS-box genes.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] A mutation of either of these genes causes the homeotic conversion of petals into sepals and of stamens into carpels.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] This also occurs in its orthologs in *A. majus*, which are DEFICIENS (*DEF*) and *GLOBOSA* (*GLO*) respectively.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] For both species the active form of binding with DNA is that derived from the heterodimer: AP3 and PI, or DEF and GLO, dimerize.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is the form in which they are able to function.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *GLO*/*PI* lines that have been duplicated in *Petunia* contain *P. hybrida GLOBOSA1* (*PhGLO1*, also called *FBP1*) and also *PhGLO2* (also called *PMADS2* or *FBP3*).
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] For the functional elements equivalent to *AP3*/*DEF* in *Petunia* there is both a gene that possesses a relatively similar sequence, called *PhDEF* and there is also an atypical B function gene called PhTM6.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic studies have placed the first three within the «euAP3» lineage, while PhTM6 belongs to that of «paleoAP3».
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] As discussed above, the floral organs of eudicotyledonous angiosperms are arranged in 4 different verticils, containing the sepals, petals, stamen and carpels.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model states that the identity of these organs is determined by the homeotic genes A, A+B, B+C and C, respectively.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In contrast with the sepal and petal verticils of the eudicots, the perigone of many plants of the family Liliaceae have two nearly identical external petaloid verticils (the tepals).
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In order to explain the floral morphology of the Liliaceae, van Tunen *et al.* proposed a modified ABC model in 1993.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] This model suggests that class B genes are not only expressed in verticils 2 and 3, but also in 1.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] It therefore follows that the organs of verticils 1 and 2 express class A and B genes and this is how they have a petaloid structure.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] This theoretical model has been experimentally proven through the cloning and characterization of homologs of the *Antirrhinum* genes *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* in a Liliaceae, the tulip *Tulipa gesneriana*.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are expressed in verticils 1,2 and 3.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* have also been isolated and characterized in *Agapanthus praecox* ssp.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] *orientalis* (Agapanthaceae), which is phylogenetically distant from the model organisms.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this study the genes were called *ApGLO* and *ApDEF*, respectively.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both contain open reading frames that code for proteins with 210 to 214 amino acids.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic analysis of these sequences indicated that they belong to B gene family of the monocotyledons.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In situ hybridization studies revealed that both sequences are expressed in verticil 1 as well as in 2 and 3.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] When taken together, these observations show that the floral development mechanism of *Agapanthus* also follows the modified ABC model.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, the C function is derived from one MADS-box type gene called *AGAMOUS* (*AG*), which intervenes both in the establishment of stamen and carpel identity as well as in the determination of the floral meristem.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Therefore, the *AG* mutants are devoid of androecium and gynoecium and they have petals and sepals in their place.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition, the growth in the centre of the flower is undifferentiated, therefore the petals and sepals grow in repetitive verticils.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *PLENA* (*PLE*) gene is present in *A. majus*, in place of the *AG* gene, although it is not an ortholog.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, the *FARINELLI* (*FAR*) gene is an ortholog, which is specific to the development of the anthers and the maturation of pollen.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Petunia*, *Antirrhinum* and in maize the C function is controlled by a number of genes that act in the same manner.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The genes that are closer homologs of *AG* in *Petunia* are *pMADS3* and *floral-binding protein 6* (*FBP6*).
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The D function genes were discovered in 1995.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are MADS-box proteins and they have a function that is distinct from those previously described, although they have a certain homology with C function genes.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are called *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN7* (*FBP7*) and *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN1L* (*FBP1l*).
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was found that, in *Petunia*, they are involved in the development of the ovule.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] Equivalent genes were later found in *Arabidopsis*, where they are also involved in controlling the development of carpels and the ovule and even with structures related to seed dispersal.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The appearance of interesting phenotypes in RNA interference studies in *Petunia* and tomato led, in 1994, to the definition of a new type of function in the floral development model.
[src:berry/abc-model-of-flower-development] The E function was initially thought to be only involved in the development of the three innermost verticils, however, subsequent work found that its expression was required in all the floral verticils.
[src:berry/acai] The **açaí palm** (/əˈsaɪ.iː/ *ə-SY-ee*, Brazilian Portuguese: [asaˈi] ⓘ; from Nheengatu *asai*), *Euterpe oleracea*, is a species of palm tree (Arecaceae) cultivated for its fruit (açaí berries, or simply açaí), hearts of palm (a vegetable), leaves, and trunk wood.
[src:berry/acai] Global demand for the fruit has expanded rapidly in the 21st century, and the tree is cultivated for that purpose primarily.
[src:berry/acai] The species is native to eastern Amazonia, especially in Brazil, mainly in swamps and floodplains.
[src:berry/acai] Açaí palms are tall, slender trees growing to more than 25 m (82 ft) tall, with pinnate leaves up to 3 m (9.8 ft) long.
[src:berry/acai] The fruit is small, round, and black-purple in color.
[src:berry/acai] The fruit became a staple food in floodplain areas around the 18th century, but its consumption in urban areas and promotion as a health food only began in the mid-1990s along with the popularization of other Amazonian fruits outside the region.
[src:berry/acai] The folk etymology says that chief Itaqui ordered all newborns put to death owing to a period of famine.
[src:berry/acai] When his own daughter gave birth and the child was sacrificed, she cried and died beneath a newly sprouted tree.
[src:berry/acai] The tree fed the tribe and was called açaí because that was the daughter's name (Iaçá) spelled backwards.
[src:berry/acai] Its specific epithet *oleracea* means "vegetable" in Latin and is a form of *holeraceus* (*oleraceus*).
[src:berry/acai] The fruit, commonly known as açaí or açaí berry, is a small, round, black-purple drupe about 25 mm (1 in) in circumference, similar in appearance to a grape, but smaller and with less pulp and produced in branched panicles of 500 to 900 fruits.
[src:berry/acai] The exocarp of the ripe fruits is a deep purple color, or green, depending on the kind of açaí and its maturity.
[src:berry/acai] The mesocarp is pulpy and thin, with a consistent thickness of 1 mm (0.04 in) or less.
[src:berry/acai] It surrounds the voluminous and hard endocarp, which contains a single large seed about 7–10 mm (0.3–0.4 in) in diameter.
[src:berry/acai] The seed makes up about 60–80% of the fruit.
[src:berry/acai] The palm bears fruit year round but the berry cannot be harvested during the rainy season.
[src:berry/acai] The açaí palm is a light-loving plant, and fruit yields greatly decrease in amount and quality if the plants are shaded.
[src:berry/acai] There are two harvests: one is normally between January and June, while the other is between August and December, producing larger volumes.
[src:berry/acai] In 2022, the state of Pará, which accounts for 90% of Brazil's total açaí economy, produced 8,158 tonnes (17,985,000 lb) of açaí berries, generating US$26 million in revenue.
[src:berry/acai] The 2022 production was 209 times greater than the volume produced in 2012.
[src:berry/acai] Children as young as 13 years old are employed as laborers to harvest the fruit, using machetes to clear paths in the rainforest, and climbing trees up to 70 feet (21 m) tall without harnesses to collect berries in the canopy, a process leading to falls and severe injuries in some children.
[src:berry/acai] A powdered preparation of freeze-dried açaí fruit pulp and skin was reported to contain (per 100 g of dry powder) 534 calories, 52 g carbohydrates, 8 g protein, and 33 g total fat.
[src:berry/acai] The carbohydrate portion included 44 g of dietary fiber with low sugar levels, and the fat portion consisted of oleic acid (56% of total fats), palmitic acid (24%), and linoleic acid (13%).
[src:berry/acai] The powder was also shown to contain (per 100 g) negligible vitamin C, 260 mg calcium, 4 mg iron, and 1002 IU vitamin A.
[src:berry/acai] Anthocyanins define the blue pigmentation of açaí and the antioxidant capacity of the plant's natural defense mechanisms and in laboratory experiments in vitro.
[src:berry/acai] Anthocyanins in açaí accounted for only about 10% of the overall antioxidant capacity in vitro.
[src:berry/acai] The Linus Pauling Institute and European Food Safety Authority state that "the relative contribution of dietary flavonoids to (...) antioxidant function in vivo is likely to be very small or negligible".
[src:berry/acai] Unlike in controlled test tube conditions, anthocyanins have been shown to be poorly conserved (less than 5%) in vivo, and most of what is absorbed exists as chemically modified metabolites destined for rapid excretion.
[src:berry/acai] A powdered preparation of freeze-dried açaí fruit pulp and skin was shown to contain cyanidin 3-O-glucoside and cyanidin 3-O-rutinoside as major anthocyanins (3.19 mg/g).
[src:berry/acai] The powdered preparation was also reported to contain twelve flavonoid-like compounds, including homoorientin, orientin, taxifolin deoxyhexose, isovitexin, scoparin, as well as proanthocyanidins (12.89 mg/g), and low levels of resveratrol (1.1 μg/g).
[src:berry/acai] In the 1980s, the Brazilian Gracie family marketed açaí as an energy drink or as crushed fruit served with granola and bananas; this demand led to the building of cottage industries and processing plants to pulp and freeze açaí for export.
[src:berry/acai] In the early 2000s, numerous companies advertised açaí products online, with many ads featuring counterfeit testimonials and products.
[src:berry/acai] Federal Trade Commission's "scams and rip-offs" list, so that by 2011 sales of açaí flattened as the fad waned.
[src:berry/acai] According to the Washington, D.C.–based Center for Science in the Public Interest thousands of consumers had trouble stopping recurrent charges on their credit cards when they canceled free trials of some açai-based products.
[src:berry/acai] In 2003, American celebrity doctor Nicholas Perricone included açaí berries among "superfoods", but such extravagant marketing claims regarding açaí as miracle cures for everything from obesity to attention-deficit disorder were challenged in subsequent studies.
[src:berry/acai] The FTC handed down an $80 million judgement in January 2012 against five companies that were marketing açaí berry supplements with fraudulent claims that their products promoted weight loss and prevented colon cancer.
[src:berry/acai] One company, Central Coast Nutraceuticals, was ordered to pay a $1.5 million settlement.
[src:berry/acai] Brazil is a major producer, particularly in the state of Pará, which alone in 2019 produced more than 1.2 million tons of açaí, an amount equal to 95% of Brazil's total.
[src:berry/acai] Several studies have implicated açaí fruit in the transmission of Chagas disease.
[src:berry/acai] This is a risk when unpasteurized uncleaned fruits are consumed, and has been found in the regions where the fruit is harvested.
[src:berry/acai] Fresh açaí has been consumed as a dietary staple in the region around the Amazon river delta for centuries.
[src:berry/acai] The fruit is processed into pulp for supply to food product manufacturers or retailers, sold as frozen pulp, juice, or an ingredient in various products from beverages, including grain alcohol, smoothies, foods, cosmetics and supplements.
[src:berry/acai] In Brazil, it is commonly eaten as **açaí na tigela**.
[src:berry/acai] In a study of three traditional Caboclo populations in the Brazilian Amazon, açaí palm was described as the most important plant species because the fruit makes up a major component of their diet, up to 42% of the total food intake by weight.
[src:berry/acai] Açaí na tigela (known in English as *açaí bowl*) is a Brazilian dessert made from frozen açaí berry purée, served in a bowl and topped with other fruit and granola.
[src:berry/acai] As of 2008, no açaí products have been evaluated by the FDA, and their efficacy is doubtful.
[src:berry/acai] As of 2009, there is no scientific evidence that açaí consumption affects body weight, promotes weight loss or has any positive health effect.
[src:berry/acai] Açaí oil is suitable for cooking or as a salad dressing, but is mainly used in cosmetics as shampoos, soaps or skin moisturizers.
[src:berry/acai] The oil compartments in açaí fruit contain polyphenols such as procyanidin oligomers and vanillic acid, syringic acid, p-hydroxybenzoic acid, protocatechuic acid, and ferulic acid, which were shown to degrade substantially during storage or exposure to heat.
[src:berry/acai] Although these compounds are under study for potential health effects, there remains no substantial evidence that açaí polyphenols have any effect in humans.
[src:berry/acai] Açaí oil is green in color, has a bland aroma, and is high in oleic and palmitic fatty acids.
[src:berry/acai] Leaves of the palm may be made into hats, mats, baskets, brooms and roof thatch for homes, and trunk wood, resistant to pests, for building construction.
[src:berry/acai] Tree trunks may be processed to yield dietary minerals.
[src:berry/acai] Comprising 80% of the fruit mass, açaí seeds may be ground for livestock food or as a component of organic soil for plants.
[src:berry/acai] Planted seeds are used for new palm tree stock, which, under the right growing conditions, can require months to form seedlings.
[src:berry/acai] Seeds may become waste in landfills or used as fuel for producing bricks.
[src:berry/acai] Orally administered açaí has been tested as a contrast agent for magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the gastrointestinal system.
[src:berry/acai] Its anthocyanins have also been characterized for stability as a natural food coloring agent.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] An **accessory fruit** is a fruit that contains tissue derived from plant parts other than the ovary.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] In other words, the flesh of the fruit develops not from the floral ovary, but from some adjacent tissue exterior to the carpel (for example, from receptacles or sepal).
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] As a general rule, the accessory fruit is a combination of several floral organs, including the ovary.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] In contrast, true fruit forms exclusively from the ovary of the flower.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] Accessory fruits are usually indehiscent, meaning that they do not split open to release seeds when they have reached maturity.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] Fruit with fleshy seeds, such as pomegranate or mamoncillo, are not considered to be accessory fruits.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] The part of apples and pears that is consumed is, in fact, the hypanthium.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] The ovary is the papery core that surrounds the apple seeds.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] As the hypanthium ripens it forms the edible tissues.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] For roses, the hypanthium is the tissue that composes the edible part of rosehips.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] Roses and apples are both members of the Rosaceae family; the fact that they have similar fruit morphology is a major consideration in placing them in the same taxonomic family.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] The edible part of the strawberry is formed, as part of the ripening process, from the receptacle of the strawberry flower.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] The true fruits (hence, containing the seeds) are the roughly 200 pips (which are, technically, achenes, a true fruit that contains a single seed from a single ovary).
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] These pips dot the exterior of the strawberry.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] The cashew apple is an oval- or pear-shaped structure that develops from the pedicel and the receptacle of the cashew flower and is technically called a hypocarpium.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] It ripens into a yellow or red structure about 5–11 cm (2–4+1⁄4 in) long.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] The true fruit of the cashew tree is a kidney–shaped drupe that grows at the end of the cashew apple; the seed inside this drupe is the cashew nut of commerce.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] The pineapple is formed when 50 to 200 unpollinated flowers coalesce in a spiral arrangement— the flowers form individually and then fuse as a single 'multiple fruit'.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] The ovaries develop into berries and the fruit forms around an intercalary spike.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] The intercalary inflorescence (cluster of flowers) results when the terminal cluster of flowers are left behind by the growth of the main axis of the plant.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] Each polygonal area on the pineapple's surface is an individual flower.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] Current research has proposed that a single class of genes may be responsible for regulating accessory fruit formation and ripening.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] A study using strawberries concluded that hormone signaling pathways involving gibberellic acid and auxin affect gene expression, and contribute to the initiation of accessory fruit development.
[src:berry/accessory-fruit] Metabolic modifications in different developing accessory fruit tissues are due to the varied distributions of compounds such as triterpenoids and steroids.
[src:berry/achene] An **achene** (/əˈkiːn/; from Ancient Greek ἀ*(*a*)* 'privative' and χαίνειν*(*khaínein*)* 'to gape'), also sometimes called **akene** and occasionally **achenium** or **achenocarp**, is a type of simple dry fruit produced by many species of flowering plants.
[src:berry/achene] Achenes are monocarpellate (formed from one carpel) and indehiscent (they do not open at maturity).
[src:berry/achene] Achenes contain a single seed that nearly fills the pericarp, but does not adhere to it.
[src:berry/achene] In many species, what is called the "seed" is an achene, a fruit containing the seed.
[src:berry/achene] The seed-like appearance is owed to the hardening of the fruit wall (pericarp), which encloses the solitary seed so closely as to seem like a seed coat.
[src:berry/achene] The fruits of buttercup, buckwheat, caraway, quinoa, amaranth, and cannabis are typical achenes.
[src:berry/achene] The achenes of the strawberry are sometimes mistaken for seeds.
[src:berry/achene] The strawberry is an accessory fruit with an aggregate of achenes on its outer surface, and what is eaten is accessory tissue.
[src:berry/achene] A rose produces an aggregate of achene fruits that are encompassed within an expanded hypanthium, which is a structure where basal portions of the calyx, the corolla, and the stamens unite with the receptacle to form a cup-shaped tube.
[src:berry/achene] A winged achene, as in maple, is called a samara.
[src:berry/achene] Some achenes have accessory hair-like structures that cause them to tumble in the wind in a manner similar to a tumbleweed.
[src:berry/achene] This type sometimes is called a tumble fruit or diaspore.
[src:berry/achene] A caryopsis or grain is a type of fruit that closely resembles an achene, but differs in that the pericarp is fused to the thin seed coat in the grain.
[src:berry/achene] An utricle is like an achene, but the fruit is bladder-like or inflated.
[src:berry/achene] Fruits of sedges are sometimes considered achenes although their one-locule ovary is a compound ovary.
[src:berry/achene] The fruit of the family Asteraceae is also so similar to an achene that it is often considered to be one, although it derives from a compound inferior ovary (with one locule).
[src:berry/achene] A special term for the Asteraceae fruit is cypsela (plural cypselae or cypselas).
[src:berry/achene] For example, the white-gray husks of a sunflower "seed" are the walls of the cypsela fruit.
[src:berry/achene] Many cypselas (e.g. dandelion) have modified calyx tissue called pappi attached that functions in biological dispersal of the seed.
[src:berry/aestivation-botany] Aestivation can be an important taxonomic diagnostic; for example Malvaceae flower buds have valvate sepals, with the exception of the genera *Fremontodendron* and *Chiranthodendron*, which have sometimes been misplaced as a result.
[src:berry/aestivation-botany] The terms used to describe aestivation are the same as those used to describe leaf vernation.
[src:berry/aggregate-fruit] An **aggregate fruit** or **etaerio** (/ɛ.ˈtɪər.i.oʊ/) is a fruit that develops from the merger of several ovaries that were separated in a single flower.
[src:berry/aggregate-fruit] In contrast, a *simple fruit* develops from one ovary, and a *multiple fruit* develops from multiple flowers.
[src:berry/aggregate-fruit] In languages other than English, the meanings of "aggregate" and "multiple" fruit are reversed, so that "aggregate" fruits merge several flowers.
[src:berry/aggregate-fruit] The differences in meaning are due to a reversal in the terminology by John Lindley, which has been followed by most English-language authors.
[src:berry/aggregate-fruit] Not all flowers with multiple ovaries form aggregate fruit; the ovaries of some flowers do not become tightly joined to make a larger fruit.
[src:berry/aggregate-fruit] As a result, many fruits form which are commonly mistaken to be of the aggregate variety.
[src:berry/aggregate-fruit] Aggregate fruits may also be accessory fruits, in which parts of the flower other than the ovary become fleshy and form part of the fruit.
[src:berry/aggregate-fruit] The individual parts of an aggregate fruit come in many forms.
[src:berry/aggregate-fruit] The components of other aggregate fruit are more difficult to define.
[src:berry/aggregate-fruit] For example, sugar apple (*Annona* spp.) fruit are made up of individual berry-like pistils fused with the receptacle.
[src:berry/agronomy] This topic of agronomy involves selective breeding of plants to produce the best crops for various conditions.
[src:berry/agronomy] Plant breeding has increased crop yields and has improved the nutritional value of numerous crops, including corn, soybeans, and wheat.
[src:berry/agronomy] It has also resulted in the development of new types of plants.
[src:berry/agronomy] For example, a hybrid grain named triticale was produced by crossbreeding rye and wheat.
[src:berry/agronomy] Triticale contains more usable protein than does either rye or wheat.
[src:berry/agronomy] Agronomy has also been instrumental for fruit and vegetable production research.
[src:berry/agronomy] Furthermore, the application of plant breeding for turfgrass development has resulted in a reduction in the demand for fertilizer and water inputs (requirements), as well as turf-types with higher disease resistance.
[src:berry/agronomy] Agronomists use biotechnology to extend and expedite the development of desired characteristics.
[src:berry/agronomy] Biotechnology is often a laboratory activity requiring field testing of new crop varieties that are developed.
[src:berry/agronomy] In addition to increasing crop yields agronomic biotechnology is being applied increasingly for novel uses other than food.
[src:berry/agronomy] For example, oilseed is at present used mainly for margarine and other food oils, but it can be modified to produce fatty acids for detergents, substitute fuels and petrochemicals.
[src:berry/agronomy] Agronomists study sustainable ways to make soils more productive and profitable.
[src:berry/agronomy] They classify soils and analyze them to determine whether they contain nutrients vital for plant growth.
[src:berry/agronomy] Common macronutrients analyzed include compounds of nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, calcium, magnesium, and sulfur.
[src:berry/agronomy] Soil is also assessed for several micronutrients, like zinc and boron.
[src:berry/agronomy] The percentage of organic matter, soil pH, and nutrient holding capacity (cation exchange capacity) are tested in a regional laboratory.
[src:berry/agronomy] Agronomists will interpret these laboratory reports and make recommendations to modify soil nutrients for optimal plant growth.
[src:berry/agronomy] Additionally, agronomists develop methods to preserve soil and decrease the effects of [erosion] by wind and water.
[src:berry/agronomy] For example, a technique known as contour plowing may be used to prevent soil erosion and conserve rainfall.
[src:berry/agronomy] Researchers of agronomy also seek ways to use the soil more effectively for solving other problems.
[src:berry/agronomy] Such problems include the disposal of human and animal manure, water pollution, and pesticide accumulation in the soil, as well as preserving the soil for future generations such as the burning of paddocks after crop production.
[src:berry/agronomy] Pasture management techniques include no-till farming, planting of soil-binding grasses along contours on steep slopes, and using contour drains of depths as much as 1 metre.
[src:berry/agronomy] Agroecology is the management of agricultural systems with an emphasis on ecological and environmental applications.
[src:berry/agronomy] This topic is associated closely with work for sustainable agriculture, organic farming, and alternative food systems and the development of alternative cropping systems.
[src:berry/agronomy] Theoretical production ecology is the quantitative study of the growth of crops.
[src:berry/agronomy] The plant is treated as a kind of biological factory, which processes light, carbon dioxide, water, and nutrients into harvestable products.
[src:berry/agronomy] The main parameters are temperature, sunlight, standing crop biomass, plant production distribution, and nutrient and water supply.
[src:berry/berry] A **berry** is a small, pulpy, and often edible fruit.
[src:berry/berry] The common usage of the term "berry" is different from the scientific or botanical definition of a berry, which refers to a fleshy fruit produced from the ovary of a single flower where the outer layer of the ovary wall develops into an edible fleshy portion (pericarp).
[src:berry/berry] The botanical definition includes many fruits that are not commonly known or referred to as berries,‍ such as grapes, tomatoes, cucumbers, eggplants, bananas, and chili peppers.
[src:berry/berry] Fruits commonly considered berries but excluded by the botanical definition include strawberries, raspberries, and blackberries, which are aggregate fruits, and mulberries, which are multiple fruits.
[src:berry/berry] Watermelons and pumpkins are giant berries that fall into the category "pepos".
[src:berry/berry] A plant bearing berries is said to be *bacciferous* or *baccate*.
[src:berry/berry] Berries are eaten worldwide and often used in jams, preserves, cakes, or pies.
[src:berry/berry] Some berries are commercially important.
[src:berry/berry] The berry industry varies from country to country as do types of berries cultivated or growing in the wild.
[src:berry/berry] Some berries such as raspberries and strawberries have been bred for hundreds of years and are distinct from their wild counterparts, while other berries, such as lingonberries and cloudberries, grow almost exclusively in the wild.
[src:berry/berry] While many berries are edible, some are poisonous to humans, such as those of deadly nightshade and pokeweed.
[src:berry/berry] Others, such as the white mulberry, red mulberry,‍ and elderberry,‍ are poisonous when unripe, but edible when ripe.
[src:berry/berry] Berries have been valuable as a food source for humans since before the start of agriculture, and remain a food source for other primates.
[src:berry/berry] They were a seasonal staple for early hunter-gatherers for thousands of years, and wild berry gathering remains a popular activity in Europe and North America today.
[src:berry/berry] In time, humans learned to store berries so that they could be used in the winter.
[src:berry/berry] Berries also began to be cultivated in Europe and other countries.
[src:berry/berry] The strawberry was mentioned by ancient Romans, who thought it had medicinal properties,‍ but it was then not a staple of agriculture.‍ Woodland strawberries began to be grown in French gardens in the 14th century.
[src:berry/berry] The musk strawberry (*F. moschata*), also known as the hautbois strawberry, began to be grown in European gardens in the late 16th century.
[src:berry/berry] Later, the Virginia strawberry was grown in Europe and the United States.‍ The most commonly consumed strawberry, the garden strawberry (*F. ananassa*), is an accidental hybrid of the Virginia strawberry and a Chilean variety *Fragaria chiloensis*.
[src:berry/berry] It was first noted by a French gardener around the mid 18th century that, when *F. moschata* and *F. virginiana* were planted in between rows of *F. chiloensis*, the Chilean strawberry would bear abundant and unusually large fruits.
[src:berry/berry] The Old English word *berie* ('berry, grape') comes from Proto-Germanic, variously reconstructed as **basją*, **bazją*, **basjom* (source also of Old Norse *ber*, Middle Dutch *bere*, German *Beere*, 'berry', Old Saxon *winberi*, Gothic *weinabasi*, 'grape'), which is of unknown origin.
[src:berry/berry] In botanical terminology, a berry is a simple fruit with seeds and pulp produced from the ovary of a single flower.
[src:berry/berry] It is fleshy throughout, except for the seeds.
[src:berry/berry] It does not have a special "line of weakness" along which it splits to release the seeds when ripe (i.e. it is indehiscent).‍ A berry may develop from an ovary with one or more carpels (the female reproductive structures of a flower).
[src:berry/berry] The seeds are usually embedded in the fleshy interior of the ovary, but there are some non-fleshy examples such as peppers, with air rather than pulp around their seeds.
[src:berry/berry] Berries under both definitions include blueberries, cranberries, lingonberries, and the fruits of many other members of the heather family, as well as gooseberries, goji berries, and elderberries.
[src:berry/berry] The fruits of some "currants" (*Ribes* species), such as blackcurrants, red currants and white currants, are botanical berries, and are treated as horticultural berries (or as soft fruit in the UK), even though their most commonly used names do not include the word "berry".
[src:berry/berry] Botanical berries not commonly known as berries include bananas,‍ tomatoes,‍ grapes, eggplants (aubergines), persimmons, watermelons, and pumpkins.
[src:berry/berry] There are several different kinds of fruits which are commonly called berries, but are not botanical berries.
[src:berry/berry] Blackberries, raspberries, and strawberries are kinds of aggregate fruit;‍ they contain seeds from different ovaries of a single flower.
[src:berry/berry] In aggregate fruits like blackberries, the individual "fruitlets" making up the fruit can be clearly seen.
[src:berry/berry] The fruits of blackthorn may be called "sloe berries",‍ but botanically are small stone fruits or drupes, like plums or apricots.
[src:berry/berry] Junipers and yews are commonly said to have berries, but these plants do not produce botanical fruits at all: they are gymnosperms, specifically conifers, not angiosperms (flowering plants).
[src:berry/berry] Their "berries" are highly-modified seed-bearing cones.
[src:berry/berry] In juniper berries, used to flavour gin, the cone scales, which are hard and woody in most conifers, are instead soft and fleshy when ripe.
[src:berry/berry] The bright red berries of yews consist of a fleshy outgrowth (aril) almost enclosing the poisonous seed.
[src:berry/berry] The resemblance of these plant structures to botanical berries provides a striking example of convergent evolution in different plant clades.
[src:berry/berry] Strawberries have been grown in gardens in Europe since the 14th century.‍ Blueberries were domesticated starting in 1911, with the first commercial crop in 1916.‍ Huckleberries of all varieties are not fully domesticated.
[src:berry/berry] Many other varieties of *Vaccinium* are likewise not domesticated.
[src:berry/berry] Many soft fruit berries require a period of temperatures between 0 and 10 °C (32 and 50 °F) for breaking dormancy.
[src:berry/berry] Plants may be hybridized with different species within the same genus; hybridization between different genus may also be possible, but more difficult.
[src:berry/berry] Some fruit not commonly referred to as berries and not always botanically berries are included by US land-grant university extension offices in their guides for berry cultivation, or in guides for identifying local wild edible and non-edible berries.
[src:berry/berry] Berries are commonly used in pies or tarts, such as blueberry pie, blackberry pie, and strawberry pie.
[src:berry/berry] Berries are often added to water and/or juiced, as in cranberry juice, which accounts for 95% of cranberry crop usage,‍ blueberry juice, raspberry juice, goji berry juice, acai juice, aronia berry juice, and strawberry juice.‍ Wine is the principal alcoholic beverage made from berries (grapes).
[src:berry/berry] Fruit wines are commonly made out of other berries.
[src:berry/berry] Currants, raisins and sultanas are examples of dried grape berries, and many other commercially important berries are available in dried form.
[src:berry/berry] Berries are perishable fruits with a short shelf life, and are often preserved by drying, freezing, pickling or making fruit preserves.
[src:berry/berry] Berries such as blackberry, blueberry, boysenberry, lingonberry, loganberry,‍ raspberry, and strawberry are used in jams and jellies.
[src:berry/berry] Berries have been used in some cultures for dyeing.
[src:berry/berry] Many berries contain juices that can easily stain, affording use as a natural dye.
[src:berry/berry] For example, blackberries are useful for making dyes, especially when ripe berries can easily release juice to produce a colorfast effect.‍ *Rubus* berries, such as blackberry, raspberry, black raspberry, dewberry, loganberry, and thimbleberry all produce dye colors.
